## .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Must replace entirely |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** | Catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Dead code |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | Works but not cancellation-aware | Blocking calls won't unblock |

### Key Pitfall: Hidden Deadlock

The original `Stop()` has a bug that carries forward: if `GetNextItem()` **blocks indefinitely**, setting `_running = false` does nothing — the thread never re-checks the flag. `Thread.Abort()` was the brute-force fix. In .NET 8, you **must** use `CancellationToken` to interrupt blocking calls cooperatively.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        // Task.Run uses the thread pool — no manual Thread management
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // Exit the loop cleanly; no ResetAbort needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false + Thread.Abort)
        await _cts.CancelAsync();

        // Wait with a timeout — replaces Thread.Sleep + IsAlive check
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)))
        {
            // Task didn't finish in time — log a warning.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill it.
            // This is by design: cooperative cancellation > corruption.
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### If You Can't Make Methods Async

When wrapping legacy synchronous code that blocks (e.g., a `BlockingCollection.Take`), pass the token into the blocking call:

```csharp
// Sync version — still uses CancellationToken
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            // BlockingCollection.Take accepts a CancellationToken
            var item = _queue.Take(token);
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

### Migration Checklist

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — non-negotiable; Abort throws at runtime in .NET 8
2. **`ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`** — the cooperative equivalent
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → delete** — no equivalent needed; `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow
4. **`volatile bool` → `CancellationToken`** — tokens integrate with `async/await`, `Task.Delay`, `BlockingCollection`, `SemaphoreSlim`, etc.
5. **`new Thread()` → `Task.Run()`** — uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread lifecycle
6. **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** — non-blocking, cancellable
7. **Audit every blocking call** — if `GetNextItem()` doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, cancellation can't interrupt it. This is the #1 source of "works on Framework, hangs on .NET 8" bugs.
